h3. Summary
It is currently not possible to share a request to an organization when creating it via [Service Desk REST API|https://docs.atlassian.com/jira-servicedesk/REST/3.6.1/]
* *Create customer request* {{POST /rest/servicedeskapi/request}}

h3. Suggestion
Allow the sharing of request to organization when creating the request via REST API

h3. Workaround
Once the request is created, use JIRA REST API to update the Organizations field:
 # Get the ID of custom field Organizations from db:
{code:java}
select * from customfield where cfname = 'Organizations';{code}
 # Get the ID of the organization itself, also from db:
{code:java}
select * from AO_54307E_ORGANIZATION;{code}
 # Use [JIRA REST API - PUT editIssue|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/7.9.2/#api/2/issue-editIssue] with this JSON body:
{code:java}
{
    "fields": {
        "customfield_10203": [3]
    }
}
{code}
 ** Replace 10203 with the ID of custom field Organizations from step 1
 ** Replace 3 with the ID of the organization from step 2
 (+) Ensure that the organization is in the Customers list of the Service Desk project

I would like to continue the suggestion proposed in -JSDSERVER-2233-.

I think it would be a good idea, that when rendering the form, the attribute "required" would be added in the fields that are mandatory.

We have injected this attribute using jquery, reading before the json payload form to know what fields are required, but sometimes it does not work, because the json payload doesn't load it.


{code:javascript}
jQuery(document).ready(function(){

	jQuery('[type=submit]').live({
	  click: function() {
	    
		 try {
			 var obj = jQuery.parseJSON(jQuery('#jsonPayload').text());
			 var objFields = obj["reqCreate"]["fields"];
			 for (var i in objFields)  {
				var field_id = objFields[i].fieldId;
				var field_required = objFields[i].required;
			 }
		 }
		catch(e){
			console.log("jsonPayload reqCreate fields undefined");
		 }		 
	}});
});	    
{code}

Right now customer notification emails can only contain the latest comment, and only for comment added and comment edited notifications. Our customers don't log into JIRA, so these comments are often hard to understand because without the full chain of comments they're out of context.

 

Our customer notification templates look like this:

{{$\{event.user.name} commented:}}

{{$\{comment}}}

 

Perhaps a solution would be to have a variable for all comments? E.g.,

{{$\{event.user.name} commented:}}

{{$\{issue.comments}}}

 

We're using Service Desk 3.5.0 and JIRA 7.3.6.

If there's a way of doing this already then please let me know.
